          "body": "The Chronicler's distinctive contribution to the Josiah account is the year-8 marker: 'while he was still a youth, he began to seek the God of his father David' (34:3). The parallel account in 2 Kings 22-23 omits this detail entirely, beginning with the temple repair. The Chronicler includes it because his theology of reform is consistently inside-out: the inner life of seeking precedes and generates the outward work of purging. Josiah was approximately sixteen when he began to seek and approximately twenty when he began to tear down altars. The four-year gap is the Chronicler's argument: you cannot reform what you have not first sought the God who owns it. The phrase 'the God of his father David' is also deliberate — David is the Chronicler's paradigmatic seeker (1 Chronicles 28:9), and Josiah's lineage is not biological but spiritual. He was born twelve generations after David, but he chose David's God as his own before any political pressure demanded it. Swindoll notes that Josiah is one of the few kings whose reign is evaluated with the unqualified Davidic formula (cf. 1 Kings 15:11 on Asa, 2 Kings 18:3 on Hezekiah). The formula means more than moral decency — it means covenantal alignment with the theological pattern David established."
