          "title": "The recovered word — Scripture lost and found",
          "body": "The discovery of the Book of the Law (34:14-15) is the chapter's narrative hinge and its most searching theological moment. The Torah had not been destroyed — it had been lost *inside the house of God* during the temple repairs. The indictment is severe: the generation that worshipped in the temple had done so without the word that defined what acceptable worship was. The word 'found' (*matsa*, 34:14, 15) carries the weight of something that should have been in hand all along but was not. Hilkiah's report to Shaphan and Shaphan's reading before the king (34:15-18) traces the word's journey from recovered scroll to royal audience — and the king's response is immediate and visceral: he tore his clothes (34:19). Cloth-tearing (*qara beged*) in the Old Testament is the conventional expression of catastrophic grief — it marks the moment when words become unbearable because they are true (cf. 2 Kings 22:11; Ezra 9:3). Josiah did not debate the scroll's authenticity, did not commission a committee to study it, did not ask whether the curses were conditional or absolute. He heard the word of God and recognized that the nation's history was a multi-generational record of exactly the covenant violations the curses described. Howard Hendricks observed that the most dangerous reader of Scripture is the one who reads it without letting it read him back. Josiah is the counter-example: the word read him and he was undone."
